Key Exam Takeaways - TTL & Pricing
TTL Concepts:
‚úÖ TTL = Content kitni der cache mein rahega
‚úÖ Short TTL = Fresh content, high origin load, expensive
‚úÖ Long TTL = Better performance, stale content risk, cheaper
‚úÖ Different content types need different TTLs
‚úÖ Static content = Long TTL, Dynamic = Short TTL
‚úÖ TTL expired = Content stale = Fetch from origin
Pricing Concepts:
‚úÖ Pay-as-you-go model - no upfront costs
‚úÖ Two main components: Data transfer + Requests
‚úÖ Regional pricing varies significantly
‚úÖ AWS to CloudFront = FREE
‚úÖ CloudFront to users = Charged (region-based)
‚úÖ Free tier: 1M requests + 50GB/month
‚úÖ Price classes control which regions = cost optimization
‚úÖ Cache hit ratio improvement = major cost savings
‚úÖ Compression = 60-90% data transfer reduction
Best Practices:
‚úÖ Match TTL to content update frequency
‚úÖ Use versioning for static assets (long TTL possible)
‚úÖ Enable compression for text-based content
‚úÖ Choose appropriate price class for audience
‚úÖ Maximize cache hit ratio
‚úÖ Use Origin Shield for high-traffic origins
‚úÖ Monitor and optimize regularly
‚úÖ Use CloudFront Functions over Lambda@Edge when possible

Final Pro Tips:

TTL strategy = Performance vs Freshness tradeoff
Pricing optimization = Caching + Compression + Right regions
Always calculate cost before deploying
Monitor CloudFront metrics for optimization opportunities
Use AWS Cost Explorer for detailed cost analysis
